\nEvolve is our midlife progression ERG that supports all colleagues' evolving life-stages and career progression.\nJune 20, 2024 -\nNatacha Dervisevic, Credit Trader, Markets\nNatacha talks with great passion about her career so far, and about the opportunities as Barclays creates an exciting and distinct proposition for our clients in Europe.\nJune 21, 2024 Article People Stories Hub -\nSchiwa Niku, Head of Europe KYC Relationship Management, Frankfurt\nFrom Trade Finance to Investment and Corporate Banking, all of Schiwa’s experience to date has made her the ideal person to lead our specialist European Know Your Customer Relationship Management (KYC RM) team in Frankfurt.\nJune 21, 2024 Article People Stories Hub -\nMBA Ambition Diversity Fellowship\nApply for the chance to receive a scholarship toward your MBA.\nJune 20, 2024 -\nBarclays Europe\nBarclays Europe is an inspiring place to be. We’re building a truly European bank with a clear mission, a huge sense of momentum and the energy of a new business.\nJune 26, 2024 Article Location overview Hub Related Content -\nDisability Confident at Barclays\nRead more about how we are a disability confident leader\nSeptember 02, 2024 Article Business overview Culture Hub Related Content -\nRead Miloš' Story\nI joined Barclays as a very junior analyst with only part-time experience. But I’d been coding since I was 15, so had some skills to offer. I like to solve problems, and there were plenty to solve, so that’s what I started doing.\nJune 18, 2024 Blog People Stories Tech Hub Related Content -\nVojtěch Král, Cloud Solutions Architect\nI joined Barclays Prague as an intern in 2012. Within 10 weeks I was working on technology that was new to me, at a scale of hundreds of gigabytes of data, and I was offered a graduate position with the business.\nJune 18, 2024 -\nZuzana, Graduate Software Developer\nZuzana’s switch from Marketing to Technology.\nJune 18, 2024 Blog People Stories Tech Hub Related Content -\nBenefits at Barclays\nWe are committed to making Barclays a great place to work: a place where everyone feels supported, included, recognised and involved.\nSeptember 12, 2024 Article Culture Hub Related Content -\nBarclays Radbroke Campus\nSee another side to Barclays in Radbroke\nJuly 11, 2024 Blog Location overview Tech -\nMalcolm, Group Chief Controls Officer\nDiscover more about CCO from Malcolm, who's a Group Chief Controls Officer.\nJanuary 08, 2024 Article People Stories Culture Hub -\nMeet Prachiti\nPrachiti Atigre is a Back End Engineer within Functions Technology at Barclays, where she commenced her journey in April 2023 through the Grace Hopper program.\nAugust 29, 2024 -\nRosie Boyce Private Banking Graduate\nMeet Rosie Boyce, Private Banking Graduate\nJanuary 05, 2024 Article People Stories Culture Hub -\nGrace Hopper\nEmbrace the future with women in technology\nAugust 28, 2024 -\nMeet Ridhima\nLearn about Ridhima's experience from being hired into Barclays through the Grace Hoppers Conference as a Data Scientist and since then been actively involved with Women in Tech initiatives\nSeptember 03, 2024 Article People Stories Hub Related Content -\nMeet Prachiti\nPrachiti commenced her journey in April 2023 through the Grace Hopper program and leverages her expertise in technologies such as Java, Salesforce, and Linux, among several others, to deliver impactful solutions.\nSeptember 03, 2024 -\nRecruitment Scams\nStay vigilant with Recruitment scams\nNovember 25, 2025 -\nMicaela, Assistant Vice President, Operational Risk\nHear how Risk is an exciting place to work to drive organisational change.\nDecember 27, 2023 Article People Stories Culture Hub -\nEmpowering Leaders Fellowship\nEmpowering Leaders Fellowship\nJanuary 09, 2024 Article Hub -\nRadbroke Campus\nLearn about life in Radbroke\nMarch 27, 2024 -\nMay 16, 2024 -\nEmployee Resource Group - Spectrum\nOur Spectrum resource group brings LGBT+ people and allies together; creating an environment where everyone is included.\nJune 06, 2024 -\nTechnology Spotlight\nTechnology and data for net zero ambitions\nJune 20, 2024 -\nDecember 13, 2024 -\nSeptember 09, 2025 -\nSeptember 24, 2025 -\nNovember 25, 2025 -\nMeet Akshat, Senior Software Engineer\nAkshat, Senior Software Engineer, reveals the key factors behind his decision to join Barclays.\nFebruary 18, 2026 Article People Stories Hub -\nMeet Georgia, Technical Product Owner\nGeorgia Lewis, a Technical Product Owner, recommends Barclays to anyone looking for a career in innovation\nFebruary 20, 2026 Article People Stories Hub -\nMeet Shweta , Cloud and DevOps Engineer\nShweta Desale, a Cloud and DevOps Engineer, says Barclays is a great place for engineers to develop\nFebruary 20, 2026 Article People Stories Hub -\nMeet Mat, Business Analyst\nMat Reddy, a Business Analyst, thinks collaboration has been key to his progress at Barclays\nFebruary 20, 2026 Article People Stories Hub -\nMeet Craig, Apprentice Software Engineer\nCraig Murray, an Apprentice Software Engineer, hasn’t been at Barclays for long – but has already come far\nFebruary 20, 2026 Article People Stories Hub -\nCristina, Innovation Engineer\nCristina, Innovation Engineer, has risen fast at Barclays – here she explains how\nFebruary 20, 2026 Article People Stories Hub -\nMeet Neha, Software Engineer\nNeha Mittal, a Software Engineer, has filled her boots with development opportunities at Barclays\nFebruary 20, 2026 Article People Stories Hub -\nMeet Erin, Test Engineer\nErin Heath, a Test Engineer, says that you never stop learning at Barclays\nFebruary 20, 2026 Article People Stories Hub -\nMarch 18, 2026 -\nMeet Kat, Systems Engineer\nKat talks about her journey in Technology at Tesco Bank\nMarch 16, 2026 Article People Stories Hub -\nMeet Mat, Product Owner\nMat talks about his journey as a Product Owner at Tesco Bank\nMarch 17, 2026 Article People Stories Hub -\nMeet Sania, Customer Service SME\nSania talks about her journey in Customer Service at Tesco Bank.\nMarch 17, 2026 Article People Stories Hub\n\n### MASTER CV (source of truth — do not invent beyond)\nDavid PERRON\nAge: 48\nPhone: +33 6 95 35 52 55\nEmail: david.perron@gmx.fr\nLocation: Paris - France\n\nSenior Finance Executive – Corporate Coverage, Trade Finance, Working Capital & Strategic Growth – Artificial Intelligence\nProfil\nSeasoned finance executive with a robust background in trade finance, working capital optimization, and structured transactions. Proven experience in building new business from greenfield, with strong sales and client acquisition activities leading to proven P&L growth, both as a sole contributor and as a team lead, while always keeping responsibility for core clients. Adept at managing large, cross-functional teams and driving strategic initiatives in high-stakes environments. Recognized for creating and scaling revenue streams, leveraging ESG principles and digital transformation. Curious mind with varied interests including AI, podcasting, and book authoring.\nKey Competences\n\t•\tTrade Finance & Working Capital Optimization\n\t•\tStructured Transactions (including Supply Chain Finance (SCF), Inventory Finance, Discounting, Export Finance)\n\t•\tLetters of Credit (LC), Bank Guarantees & Commodity Finance\n\t•\tP&L Management & Revenue Optimization\n\t•\tDue Diligence, Negotiation & Deal Structuring\n\t•\tDigital Transformation, Fintech Partnership & Collaboration\n\t•\tLeadership & International Team Management\n\t•\tRisk Management, KYC/AML & Regulatory Compliance (Basel II/III)\n\t•\tBusiness Development & Client Relationship Management\n\t•\tESG & Sustainability Initiatives\n\t•\tStrategic Communication & Stakeholder Engagement\n\t•\tSales and Sales Management\n\t•\tFront Office\nStudies\nExecutive Master in Artificial Intelligence for Innovative Managers\nInstitut Mines-Télécom Business School – 2025 (equivalent MIT Sloan)\nThesis: Retail vision, scan detect optimize in store sales with Video Learning Models and Augmented Reality.\nMaster in International Finance\nESC Rouen, France\nThesis: Impact of the OECD arrangement on Export Credit Agencies\nMaster in Business & Management, major Corporate Finance\nPôle Universitaire Léonard de Vinci\nProfessional Experience\nAEQUITAS CONSULTUS – Founder | 2025 -\n\t•\tTrade Finance and Working Capital advisory on sales development and Artificial Intelligence integration.\n\t•\tPodcasts on AI impact on banking and finance. (see below for link) \nJPMORGAN AG, Paris | 2020 – 2024\nHead of Trade and Working Capital Sales – France, Italy, Belgium & Luxembourg\nMandated to create the franchise and grow revenues\n\t•\tBuilt and scaled a new Trade & Working Capital franchise, achieving a 6x revenue increase and full P&L growth within four years.\n\t•\tOriginated and structured complex financial transactions including SCF, titrisation, discounting, export finance, and working capital optimization; rigorous due diligence on each deal.\n\t•\tEstablished and led a strategic partnership with the fintech Taulia for joint client acquisition and sales activities, showcasing a successful bank-fintech collaboration model.\n\t•\tLed and mentored multicultural teams across multiple countries, ensuring seamless collaboration and performance improvement.\n\t•\tCollaborated with legal counsel, external auditors, compliance officers, and credit teams in a Basel II/III regulatory and KYC/AML framework.\n\t•\tReceived the Adam Smith Award (2021) for the best SCF deal with Bridgestone, integrating ESG factors and achieving high EcoVadis ratings.\n\t•\tEnhanced internal communications and stakeholder relationships, including interactions with public authorities such as the Ministry of Finance.\n\t•\tActive in public bodies and treasury associations.\n\t•\tMarket event organisation and speaker.\nBARCLAYS CORPORATE, Paris | 2013 – 2020\nHead of Trade & Working Capital Origination – France, Belgium & NL\nMandated to diversify sources of revenues to grow and limit attrition\n\t•\tDiversified revenue streams by developing a stable EUR 3 Billion portfolio through innovative financing solutions.\n\t•\tOriginated and structured tailor-made trade finance solutions (Letters of Credit, Bank Guarantees, SCF, Receivables Finance) for multinational corporations, including CAC 40 companies and large global traders.\n\t•\tLed a high-performing team of up to eight members, ensuring efficient deal execution and continuous professional development. Hiring, training, leading.\n\t•\tRestructured team size to optimize operational costs while maintaining service excellence.\n\t•\tActively participated in the European senior leadership team and business committees, contributing to strategic decision-making and regional growth.\nBARCLAYS CORPORATE, Paris | 2011 – 2013\nTrade & Working Capital Origination – France & Belgium\n\t•\tDesigned and implemented financing structures tailored for French and Belgian corporate clients, incorporating off-balance sheet solutions and border receivable finance.\n\t•\tWorked closely with clients to understand their unique financial challenges and delivered innovative trade finance products.\nJPMORGAN CHASE BANK NA, Paris | 2007 – 2011\nSenior Sales – Treasury Services, Vice President\n\t•\tDeveloped new business and managed existing portfolios, focusing on cash management, short-term investment solutions, and trade services for high-profile clients.\n\t•\tEngaged in strategic lobbying at head office level to expand the bank's franchise in France, coordinating directly with group treasurers and export finance heads.\nHSBC, Paris | 2006 – 2007\nTrade & Cash Management Advisor\n\t•\tBuilt and maintained a portfolio of multinational corporations, providing payment solutions, cash management services, and comprehensive trade finance products.\n\t•\tContributed to HSBC's Global Transaction Banking initiatives within the Corporate, Investment Banking and Markets departments.\nWILLIS, Paris | 2005 – 2006\nInsurance Broker – Financial & Political Risks – Sales\n\t•\tSales role with intermediation between corporates and insurance companies.\n\t•\tAnalyzed commercial contracts and financial clauses to tailor risk insurance policies for international trade and foreign investment activities.\n\t•\tFacilitated the development of custom insurance solutions, ensuring clients were adequately protected against diverse financial risks.\nLanguages\n\t•\tFrançais: Native\n\t•\tAnglais: Fluent\nVoluntary Commitments\n\t•\tLed the French Red Cross county unit for 17 years, managing emergency response operations during crises alike Balkan war and coordinating first aid initiatives.\n\t•\tAwarded a Bronze Medal for exemplary service in humanitarian assistance.\nInterests\nMentoring, off-piste skiing, scuba diving, Cross-Fit, and competitive shooting.\nProfessional links Talks and Interviews\nLinkedIn: www.linkedin.com/in/davidperron\n\nYouTube Channel: http://www.youtube.com/@DavidPerron_Fr\nIn a world where AI is revolutionizing finance, banks and financial institutions are at a crossroads. How can they harness the power of artificial intelligence to optimize working capital, enhance risk assessment, and automate trade finance processes? This podcast is dedicated to demystifying AI and its impact on banking and finance.\nCivic & Military Engagement\n\t•\tInstitut des Hautes Etudes de Défense Nationale (IHEDN) - Auditeur Jeune\nSelective national defence and geopolitical studies programme run by the French Prime Minister's office. Covers strategic intelligence, national security, defence policy, and international relations. Cohort of junior professionals from public and private sectors.\n\t•\tPréparation Militaire Supérieure - Etat-Major Marine Nationale\nCompleted advanced military staff college officer preparation with the French Navy (Marine Nationale). Assigned to military intelligence.\n\t•\tFrench Red Cross - County Unit Leader for 17 years\nManaged emergency response and first aid operations at national crisis scale (including Balkan conflict deployments). Bronze Medal for exemplary humanitarian service.\n\n\n### CANDIDATE PREFERENCES\n{'preferred_roles': ['Head of', 'Managing Director', 'Director', 'VP', 'Chief'], 'preferred_sectors': ['banking', 'corporate banking', 'transaction banking', 'applied AI', 'enterprise software'], 'preferred_geographies': ['France', 'United Kingdom', 'Benelux', 'DACH', 'Switzerland', 'Nordics', 'Iberia', 'Italy', 'Europe (remote)', 'Canada'], 'target_companies': [], 'excluded_companies': []}\n\n\nRespond with a single valid JSON object. Do not wrap it in prose or code fences."}], 'model': 'claude-opus-4-6', 'system': 'SCORING PROMPT — Fit & Seniority Gate\n\nYou receive:\n1. A job posting (title, company, location, full description).\n2. A master CV (source of truth for the candidate\'s real experience).\n3. Candidate preferences (preferred roles, sectors, geographies, target companies, excluded companies).\n\nYour task is two-fold:\n\n## A. Seniority gate (hard filter)\n\nClassify the posting\'s seniority as exactly one of:\n- "junior"   — 0-3 years, Analyst / Associate / Intern / Graduate / Stagiaire / Apprenti.\n- "mid"      — 3-7 years, Manager / Senior Associate / Lead contributor without team ownership.\n- "senior"   — 7+ years, Senior Manager / Head of / Director / VP / Principal / team or P&L ownership.\n- "executive"— C-suite / Chief / Managing Director / Partner / GM.\n- "unknown"  — the posting does not give enough signal.\n\n**Rule:** If seniority is "junior" OR "mid" → the posting is discarded regardless of any other factor (the candidate is a senior / executive profile).\n\nBase your classification on: explicit titles, years-of-experience requirements, scope described (team ownership, budget, external stakeholders, regulators), vocabulary ("lead", "head", "own", "P&L" vs "support", "assist", "contribute to").\n\n## B. Fit score (only if seniority passes the gate)\n\nReturn an integer 0-100 reflecting how well the candidate\'s real experience (from the master CV) matches this specific posting. Consider:\n- Sector alignment (banking / fintech / AI / enterprise software / ...).\n- Functional alignment (sales, transformation, coverage, strategy, GTM, ...).\n- Geography fit.\n- Presence of named target/excluded companies.\n- Preferred roles / sectors list hits.\n- Whether the master CV has direct, indirect, or no evidence for the core requirements.\n\nScoring anchors:\n- 90-100: strong direct match, few gaps, likely top candidate.\n- 75-89: good match with one or two addressable gaps.\n- 60-74: relevant but meaningful gaps.\n- 40-59: adjacent, would need significant repositioning.\n- 0-39: weak fit.\n\nNever invent experience the master CV does not contain.\n\n## Output contract\n\nReturn a single JSON object:\n```json\n{\n  "seniority": "senior",\n  "pass_seniority_gate": true,\n  "fit_score": 0,\n  "sector": "banking",\n  "rationale": "3-5 lines, factual, citing specific matches and gaps from the master CV."\n}\n```\nIf `pass_seniority_gate` is false, `fit_score` must be 0.\n', 'temperature': 0.2}}
